title: Observe traces with OpenTelemetry
content:
OpenTelemetry is a collection of APIs, SDKs, and tools. You can use it to instrument, generate, collect, and export telemetry data (metrics, logs, and traces) to help analyze your software’s performance and behavior. This topic describes how to use OpenTelemetry to observe and analyze the performance of Service Management.

Overview

This diagram illustrates the architecture of the OpenTelemetry solution.

Before using the OpenTelemetry solution, be aware of the following:

  • You'll need to install some OpenTelemetry services including Operation, Collector, and certificate management. These services will consume resources in your environment, such as one CPU and 2 GB of memory.
  • It will create a new namespace cert-manager in your Kubernetes cluster.
  • The installation of OpenTelemetry will result in rolling restarts of some Service Management services.
  • The default services for observation include:
    Service Pod
    Platform

    itom-xruntime-gateway, itom-xruntime-serviceportal, itom-xruntime-platform

    Note: Asynchronous EMS operations such as Create or Update aren't supported.
    Smart Analytics smarta-search
    Integration Studio itom-xie
    Suite Administration itom-bo-ats, itom-bo-config, itom-bo-login, itom-bo-user

Prerequisite

Make sure you have a functional and reliable internet connection to download images from dockerhub.

Install OpenTelemetry

  1. Download the SMA-monitor-<version>.tar.gz package from ITOM marketplace.
  2. Upload the package to the control plane node or bastion node.
  3. Unzip the package and go to the opentelmetry_auto_install folder. The default service versions are:
    • OpenTelemetry Collector: 0.57.0
    • OpenTelemetry Operator: 0.29.1 
  4. (Optional) To install the latest version of OpenTelemetry, remove the .tgz file under ./opentelmetry_auto_install/src, download the latest package from OpenTelemetry helm chart website, and then upload the downloaded files to ./opentelmetry_auto_install/src.
  5. Run ./install_otel.sh to install OpenTelemetry.
    Running this script will install OpenTelemetry Operation and Collector, create OpenTelemetry instrumentation, add an annotation for Service Management to expose traces to OpenTelemetry Collector, and create a configuration file (configmap opentelemetry-collector) for OpenTelemetry Collector. The script will create a new namespace cert-manager in your Kubernetes cluster.
  6. Run the following command to check if all pods are up and running: 
    kubectl get pods -A |grep -v 1/1 |grep -v 2/2 |grep -v 3/3 |grep -v 4/4 |grep -v Com

  This command returns a list of abnormal pods. If it returns no results, all pods are ready.

Configure instrumentation 

Automatic instrumentation with Java uses a Java agent JAR that you can attach to any Java 8+ application. It dynamically injects bytecode to capture telemetry from many popular libraries and frameworks. You can use it to capture telemetry data at the “edges” of an app or service, such as inbound requests, outbound HTTP calls, and database calls.

The following steps define the data collection behavior (sampler) for Java Agent. Sampling controls the spans you send to your observability back end, resulting in lower ingest costs. 

  1. Run this command to configure instrumentation: 
    kubectl  edit instrumentation -n <namespace> smax-instrumentation
    where namespace indicates the namespace of the service you want to observe.
  2. Locate the sampler section and update the value for type parameter based on your business requirements: 
      sampler: 
    type: <samplerMode>

    Values for the type parameter can be:
    always_on - Sampler that always samples spans, regardless of the parent span’s sampling decision. 
    always_off - Sampler that never samples spans, regardless of the parent span’s sampling decision. 
    traceidratio - Sampler that samples probabilistically based on rate. 
    parentbased_always_on - (default) Sampler that respects its parent span’s sampling decision, but otherwise always samples. 
    parentbased_always_off - Sampler that respects its parent span’s sampling decision, but otherwise never samples. 
    parentbased_traceidratio - Sampler that respects its parent span’s sampling decision, but otherwise samples probabilistically based on rate. 

Export to the back end

To visualize and analyze your traces, you‘ll need to export them to different back ends based on your environments, such as AWS OpenSearch, Jaeger.

Export to AWS OpenSearch

Service Management configurations

Note that the endpoint value must include your pipeline endpoint (for example, https://<pipeline-endpoint>.us-east-1.osis.amazonaws.com), and the service value must be osis.

  1. Run the following command to open the ConfigMap for opentelemetry-collector: 
    kubectl edit cm -n <namespace> opentelemetry-collector
  2. If you want to expose the data to OpenSearch, locate the relay section and change it to the following:  
    data: 
  relay: | 
    exporters: 
      logging: {} 
      otlphttp:
        traces_endpoint: "https://pipeline-endpoint.us-east-1.osis.amazonaws.com/v1/traces"
        auth:
          authenticator: sigv4auth
        compression: none
  3. Locate the extensions section and add the sigv4auth extension. 
        extensions:
      sigv4auth:
        region: "us-east-1"
        service: "osis"
  4. Locate the service section and add sigv4auth to service and otlphttp to traces. 
        service:
      extensions: [sigv4auth]
      pipelines:
        traces:
          exporters: [otlphttp]

AWS configurations

  1. Go to AWS Management Console and search for EKS.
  2. Find your EKS cluster name and click it to navigate to the details page.
  3. Switch to the Compute tab and find Node groups.
  4. Click Group name. On the details tab page, find the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the cluster.
  5. Click the link to open Node IAM role ARN.
  6. On the displayed page, click Add permissions to add the following: 
    {
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": [
                "osis:*"
            ],
            "Resource": "*"
        }
    ]
}

Export to Jaeger

  1. Run the following command to open the ConfigMap for opentelemetry-collector: 
    kubectl edit cm -n <namespace> opentelemetry-collector
  2. If you want to expose the data to Jaeger, locate the relay section and change it to the following:  
    data: 
  relay: | 
    exporters: 
      logging: {} 
      jaeger: 
        endpoint: "http://jaeger-collector.default.svc.cluster.local:14250" 
        tls: 
          insecure: true
  3. Locate the pipelines section and add Jaeger as the exporter. 
          pipelines: 
        traces: 
          exporters: 
          - logging 
          - jaeger

Configure filters

  1. Run the following command to open the ConfigMap for opentelemetry-collector: 
    kubectl edit cm -n <namespace> opentelemetry-collector
  2. Locate the processors section.  
        processors: 
      batch: {} 
      filter: 
        traces: 
          span: 
          - name == "/health/**" 
          - name == "/bo/health" 
          - name == "/bo/health/**" 
          - name == "/*"

    Some out-of-the-box filters are available for use. You can add or remove them based on your own requirements.

  3. Locate the pipelines section and change it to the following: 
          pipelines: 
        logs: 
        metrics: 
        traces: 
          exporters: 
          - logging 
          - jaeger 
          processors: 
          - batch 
          - filter
